3.2  Capacity of participants and consortium as a whole  
Our RECREATE consortium consists of 21 partners from 9 different EU countries (Fig.17). Overall, we are highly multidisciplinary and exhibit very complementary expertise and competences. We are led by Politecnico di Milano (POLIMI), which is the 1st public technical university in Italy, the 6th in Europe in the area “Engineering” (https://www.topuniversities.com/universities/politecnico-di-milano). We will participate with 3 different groups, namely the Department of Chemistry, Materials and Chemical Engineering “Giulio Natta” (https://www.cmic.polimi.it, with project coordinator Prof. G. Griffini, green solvolysis, smart resins), the Department of Mechanical Engineering (https://www.mecc.polimi.it, electrofragmentation, AI-based decision support systems), and METID (https://www.metid.polimi.it/), which will be engaged in the co-design and realization of innovative learning resources in collaboration with GRIFO, for the realization of MOOCs, serious gaming approaches to composite circularity education and digital twins (https://www.grifomultimedia.it/en/home-en/). We have a well-established and documented experience as participants and coordinators of EU-funded research projects, and researchers from the two Departments are commonly engaged in several projects concerning circular economy, composite recycling, and smart polymers. Moreover, we will have direct access to some of the European university networks we and the other academic partners are currently part of (e.g., ENHANCE, IDEA League, Alliance4Tech), for an efficient replication of the innovative learning tools developed in our project. The other research partners involved in RECREATE as technology providers are:  
• Tampere University (TAU), with recognized expertise in polymers and composites characterization (https://www.tuni.fi/en/research/plastics-and-elastomertechnology), and with unique specialized facilities for single-fiber mechanical testing (https://fibrobotics.com/);  
• Fraunhofer IWU and WKI (FRAUNHOFER), leading the activities of design for disassembly aimed at the reuse of various EoL composite parts. FRAUNHOFER labs are well equipped with different NDT technologies such as active/passive thermography, X-ray Computer Tomography, ultrasound monitoring and radar-based technologies, that will be crucial for the assessment of defects and for the selection of reusable EoL parts. Information about FRAUNHOFER capabilities and instrumental facilities are available at: https://ati.ec.europa.eu/technologycentre/fraunhofer-institute-machine-tools-and-forming-technology-fraunhofer-iwu; https://www.iwu.fraunhofer.de/de/forschung/leistungsangebot/kompetenzen-von-a-bis-z/nachhaltigkeit-undcircular-economy.html;  
• Icam Ouest (ICAM), in charge of the activities dedicated to thermal reshaping of GFRCs, as a follow up of recent internal positive achievements (https://en.icam.fr/innovative-structures-and-materials/);  
• University of Patras (UPAT), expert in the development of dedicated digital tools, IoT, big data analysis, socioeconomic sustainability assessment and LCA/LCC with particular reference to the case of composite circular economy;  
• Centre national de la recherche scientifique (CNRS), expert in laser-based technologies (https://pimm.artsetmetiers.fr/en/equipes/laser-laser-processes), will lead all the activities related to composite part dismantling and machining for repair. A link demonstrating available laser facilities is available at https://youtu.be/J9jUu_7bFTs  
Fig.  
17 

Geographical distribution of RECREATE 


The role of key-technology providers will be completed by Associated with document Ref. Ares(2022)3823781 - 20/05/2022 Iris Technology Development (IRIS, see https://www.iris-eng.com/), that will develop an innovative recognition and sorting technology based on laser induced breakdown spectroscopy (LIBS). The company is already owner of AI-based NIR technology for fast recognition and sorting: VISUM InLine, an Industrial NIR analyzer for real-time and continuous chemical composition monitoring adapted to several types of geometries and unit operations and unit process machinery. Rescoll (RESCOLL) and Invent (INVENT, see https://www.invent-gmbh.de/en/unternehmen/forschung/, https://www.invent-gmbh.de/en/unternehmen/fertigung/, https://www.invent-gmbh.de/en/unternehmen/produktentwicklung/) will be responsible for the design and development of modular composite structures based on detachable joints and dedicated reversible adhesives. Some of our research partners (POLIMI, FRAUNHOFER, TAU) are partners of the Vanguard Initiative (https://www.s3vanguardinitiative.eu/) and already cooperating in other common projects about circular economy. This will help to guarantee a smooth start of our project without delays, an efficient monitoring of the advancement of the activities, and an effective platform for targeted dissemination and stakeholder engagement actions.  
Two recycling SMEs, namely Cobat Compositi (COBAT COMPOSITI) and Carbon Clean-Up (Carbon Cleanup), will play an important twofold role in our project:  
• they will select and provide suitable sizes, geometries and amounts of EoL composite parts to us, after a careful mapping of available waste at EU level;  
• they will validate the new technologies and products developed in the frame of our project, performing a techno-economical evaluation of the competitivity of the proposed solution in comparison to what is currently available in the market (e.g., recycled CF from pyrolysis).  
Realization of demonstrators, integrating all the key technologies developed in our project, will be assigned to both SMEs like REST UG and BENASEDO, and large companies like EDAG engineering, GEVEN SPA (https://www.geven.com/official-home-page/test-laboratories/) and HEAD Sport GmbH. All these companies possess dedicated testing facilities where demonstration of the case studies developed in our project will be carried out in relevant industrial environment (TRL6). One of the demonstration activities focused on remanufacturing and reuse of large polyester/vinylester GFRC materials will be led by Gaiker (GAIKER), a deep-tech RTO dedicated to transfer relevant technologies to the market. Within this framework, GAIKER will implement up to TRL6 the T-assisted reshaping approach developed at lower TRL(3) by ICAM during our project, thus ultimately improving composites circularity in relevant industrial sectors (mobility, transportation).  
Our industrial partners will be supported in the formalization of appropriate sustainable circular business cases by Giacomelli-Media (G_MEDIA), which possess relevant expertise in delivering international training programs for companies in energy and circular economy sectors (see www.circularbusinessacademy.com). G_MEDIA will also be the responsible partner for the dissemination activities, where they will be supported by sectoral associations focused on composites and remanufacturing (AVK and APRA Europe, respectively). G_MEDIA possesses a vast and diverse network of industrial contacts including central-east Europe, and could engage stakeholders potentially very interested in the results of our RECREATE project.  
Finally, dedicated competences in humanities and social sciences are guaranteed by the presence of METID in our consortium, with the support of GRIFO Multimedia for gamification and realization of relevant digital tools, as well as by the activities undertaken by UPAT for the development of an integrated environmental, social and economic sustainability assessment. Dedicated activities concerning Open Sciences and Gender inclusion will be continuously monitored by POLIMI, which will be leading a task in WP9 (T9.4) fully dedicated to these aspects.  

